# Rust Ownership Model

Related: [[Memory Safety]], [[Borrowing Rules]], [[Lifetimes]]

## Overview

Rust uses an **ownership system** to manage memory without a garbage collector. Every value has a single *owner*, and when the owner goes out of scope, the value is dropped.

![[ownership-diagram.png]]

## Key Rules

1. Each value has exactly one owner
2. When the owner goes out of scope, the value is dropped
3. Ownership can be transferred via `move`

See also: [[Move Semantics]] and [[Copy Trait]]

N> For a deeper dive, see [[The Rust Book|Chapter 4]].

## Code Example

```rust
fn main() {
    let s1 = String::from("hello");
    let s2 = s1; // s1 is moved to s2
    // println!("{}", s1); // ERROR: s1 is no longer valid
    println!("{}", s2);
}
```

